<TITLE> Sensex rises 3 pct on US crisis plan hopes </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Mumbai, Sep 19 (bdnews24.com/Reuters)  The BSE Sensex rose more than 3 percent on Friday, joining a global rebound on hopes a resolution will be found to tame the crisis that has reshaped the global banking industry and threatened the financial system. Shares in export-focused outsourcing companies and banks that had taken a heavy pounding led the rise as investors picked bargains as financial authorities in the United States and other countries moved to calm credit problems. By 11:15 a.m., the 30-share benchmark index was up 3.2 percent, or 424.88 points, at 13,740.48, with all components rising. It rose as much as 3.7 percent in early trade. "If it sustains for a few more days then it could lead to a rally. We need to watch out," Sandeep Shenoy, strategist at PINC Research, said. Asian stocks rose after Wall Street had its best day in six years on Thursday boosted by the likelihood of a more comprehensive solution to the credit crisis than the current piecemeal approach. Traders said the outlook for Indian shares would depend upon foreign fund flows. The funds have pulled out $1.7 billion this month, with the outflow accelerating after Lehman Brothers collapsed rattling investor confidence. The BSE index has lost nearly a third this year on foreign withdrawals of $9 billion. In comparison, the market had risen 47.1 percent in 2007 when overseas portfolio investors moved in a record $17.4 billion. Outsourcers, which count US financial services firms among their top clients, rose on hopes a solution to the financial crisis will help them protect billings. Infosys Technologies rose 3.6 percent to 1,578 rupees and leader Tata Consultancy Services gained 5.4 percent to 759 rupees. No. 2 lender ICICI Bank climbed 3.4 percent to 595.30 rupees after dropping nearly 12 percent in the previous four sessions. HDFC Bank rose 4.2 percent to 1,272 rupees and top mortgage lender Housing Development Finance Corp gained 5.8 percent to 2.255 rupees. The sector index advanced 2 percent. Reliance Industries rose 1.5 percent to 1,962 rupees after the Business Standard daily said the company was likely to invest 100 billion rupees ($2.2 billion) more for gas production. The stock is down 8 percent in September. In the broader market, gainers overwhelmed losers by almost three to one on volume of 82.4 million shares. The 50-share NSE index rose 2.8 percent to 4,151.60. Elsewhere in the region, Karachi's 100-share index was down 0.03 percent at 9,199.88, while Colombo's All-share index rose 1.5 percent to to 2,254.60. STOCKS ON THE MOVE Videocon Industries rose 5.7 percent to 229.70 rupees after it said its joint venture firm had completed acquisition of the Brazilian oil assets of Encana Corp. Phoenix Mills rose 10.1 percent to 157.55 rupees after a block deal on the BSE representing 1.4 percent holding at 151.5 rupees a share. Godawari Power & Ispat rose 5.1 percent to 159.70 rupees after it said its unit had entered an agreement with the central Chhattisgarh state government to set up a 1,000 megawatt power project. TOP THREE BY VOLUME Jaiprakash Associates on 6.4 million shares IFCI on 4.8 million shares Reliance Natural Resources on 3.7 million share
